content:
✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: It solves the problem, meets the constraints, and includes diverse test cases. It also allows others to benefit to further Sudoku-solving algorithm development.

❌ Rejected the contribution.
Comment: Solid clash but too hard in reverse

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: itertools.combinations(digits, r=2) is your friend (in Python). The Goal is a little hard to understand, but once you know you need to return a pair that has an expected sum, it is easier.

Goal
* Please add "." at the end of each sentence.

* Suggest to change "available" to "possible".

* Suggest to change "rules" to "rule" (twice).

* Suggest to change "are only relevant to state, that" to "states that".

* Please do not format "1-9" as a variable. Instead, please format it like this: "{{1}}-{{9}}".

Input
* Please change "used" to "filled" (twice) for consistency of terminology.

* Please change "sum of resulting group" to "result group sum" for consistency of terminology.

Output
* Please mention the output integers should be in ascending order.

Constraints
* Please change "used" to "filled" for consistency of terminology.

* Please do not format "1..9" as a variable. Instead, please format it like this: "{{1}}-{{9}}" (also - instead of .. for consistency).

* Please change "pair of number" to "pair of numbers".

Stub generator
* Please change "used" to "filled" for consistency of terminology.

Thanks.

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: i love sudoku
Thank you for your comment, fixed corresponding issues and also applied a couple of other minor changes for consistency

Thanks

Noted about itertools, but I believe it is easier to go with sets with current task of finding pairs.

I initially thought about making 3rd parameter, which would define amount of empty cells, so player would need to add exactly N digits to solve the problem with minimum code, however, I've considered it might be too hard for clash of code and even harder to figure our for reverse mode.

So maybe one day I'll overcome my laziness and make it an easy-medium solo puzzle :)

If I recall correctly, reverse would still display test cases names, and for that purpose, names are kept as clear as possible.

Also, the idea behind it should be pretty easy to understand from last testcase, displaying the whole set.

I just got this in Reverse and it was way too hard. Solved it in 10 minutes as a top 30 clasher, but most clashers got 0% (I was the only non-bot to get >0%) because it was very hard to figure out what was happening without a statement.

I managed to guess roughly what was happening, but I had no idea it was relating to Sudoku and never noticed any hints in the test case names.

I suggest disabling Reverse mode.
Thanks for your feedback, disabling reverse mode then I guess

Thank you for making the changes. Two more fixes:

Goal
* Please change "is states" to "states".

Input
* Please change "used" to "filled".

Thanks.
With your suggestions fixed, would you be so kind to add an approval?
I haven't written any code to test the cases, so I'm not in a position to approve your contribution. Sorry about that.
I see, thanks anyway for your contribution :)
